class Solution {
    public int numberOfSubstrings(String s) {
        int[] count = new int[3];
        int res = 0, left = 0;
        for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {
            count[s.charAt(right) - 'a']++;
            while (count[0] > 0 && count[1] > 0 && count[2] > 0) {
                res += s.length() - right;
                count[s.charAt(left++) - 'a']--;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses a sliding window approach with two pointers, maintaining a count of characters 'a', 'b', and 'c' within the current window. When all three characters are present, it calculates the number of valid substrings ending at the current 'right' index and updates the result accordingly.
